:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Local Government Association (LGA) is the national voice of local government.  We work with councils to support, promote and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">improve local government.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are a politically-led, cross party organisation which works on behalf of councils to ensure local government has a strong, credible voice with national government.  We aim to influence and set the political agenda on the issue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s that matter to councils so they are able to deliver local solutions to national problems.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The LGA covers every part of England and Wales, supporting local government as the most efficient and accountable part of the public sector.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ofsted has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, in two consecutive years, highlighted the poor responsiveness of further education provision to local economic conditions, and the limited attention paid to equipping young people with the skills and experience to take jobs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Councils regularly identify t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">he skills system as one of the greatest barriers to local growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The current</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> funding system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> financially rewards providers for passing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">high numbers of qualifications, has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">led to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">mismatches</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> in the skills </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">young people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">possess and the needs of the local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">job</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> market</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ocal authorities are seeking to work with providers to ensure young people are trained for jobs in the local economy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">national funding and performance incentives discourage collaboration and innova</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> practice that responds to local need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ocal partnerships - including providers, employers and enabled by councils - can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">create and lead </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a coherent and responsive mix of skills provision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">focused on supporting young people’s transiti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on into th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e local labour market, but funding reform and devolution is necessary to achieve this.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Ofsted’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">emphasis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">in some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ocal authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> the percentage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">of young people unknown </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">is as high as 23 per cent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">misleading</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nly 1 council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">above 20 per </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of young people unknown</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Only 7 councils have more than 10 per cent young people unknown, and all had reduced this proportion over the last year by as much as 13 per cent – a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n improvement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not noted by the report.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Further Education</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Councils have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">duty to secure suitable education and training provisi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on for all young people aged 16-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">19, and to encourage enable and assist young people’s participation, and a responsibility to promote local growth.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ofsted has, in two consecutive years, highlighted the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">poor responsiveness of further education provision to local economic conditions,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the limited attention paid to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">equipping young people with the skills and experience to take jobs</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This has serious repercussions for employers, young people and, at an an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nual public investment of £7.78 billion, the taxpayer.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Councils regularly identify the skills system as one of the greatest barriers to local growth. It is a structural issue created by the national lagged </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">learner </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">number funding system that financially re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wards providers for passing high numbers of qualifications, rather than for helping young people towards a job or helping employers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">meet their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">skills needs. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This has led to skills mismatches, where far too many young people put their effort into courses </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">unlikely to lead to a local job. Our research has shown that, in 2011/12 post-16 providers trained 94,000 hair and beauty technicians for 18,000 jobs. Meanwhile the construction sector, which has since identified significant skills shortages, providers tra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ined around123,000 people for around 275,000 advertised jobs.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> nationally controlled funding system </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will struggle to remedy this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">because</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> national economy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a composite of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> many different local economies. There are 2.23 million local business units </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">across England, 99 per cent of which employ fewer than 100 people and the majority operate in local economies. It is our concern that, without reform, the evolving public service landscape will struggle to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">work </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">coherently with employers in ways that help y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oung people. Our analysis suggests there are three reasons for this:</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uccessive administrations have sought to build and manage relationships with employers from the centre. This has created a supply-driven model, which encourages services on the ground t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o establish relationships with employers based on the need to meet </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">national service delivery obligations, rather than the skills needs of employers over the short, medium and long term.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ervices are fragmented across eight departments and agencies t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hat separately fund many thousands of providers and individually task them to work with employers. The evolving complexity of services is difficult to coordinate from the centre and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, therefore, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">struggles to deliver the level of simplicity, stability and su</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pport all employers say they want, and the majority need, in order to participate. </span></li></ul><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oung people are not being sufficiently well informed to make positive choices that can influence ‘learner-led’ provision </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">so as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to best improve the prospects of finding wo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rk. Government has devolved the responsibility for providing careers advice to schools but without </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">providing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the resources to deliver it; three-quarters are failing to provide adequate service</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ul><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Around the country local authorities are seeking to work wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">th providers to ensure young people are trained for jobs in the local economy, identified through quality local labour market information or through linking to local investment plans and developments. Examples are available in our Hidden Talents report, in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cluding some City Deals, Community Budgets and many council led initiatives. Local models have real impact, and been better able to join-up with employment provision and other services, attract additional private sector investment, and trial payment by res</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ults models.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Good practice exists in spite of the system rather than because of it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n many places the national funding and performance incentives discourage collaboration and innovati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> practice that responds to local need.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> In our recent survey, almost</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 90 per cent of councils felt that they do not have sufficient influence to ensure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">funding enables young people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">skills </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">needed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">secure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> jobs in the local area. More than 60 per cent felt that the Education Funding Agency was driven </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the concerns of providers, than by employers or young people.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We want local partnerships - including providers, employers and enabled by councils - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> become accountable for creating and leading a coherent and responsive mix of skills provision focused o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n supporting young people’s transition </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the local labour market. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Significant progress in this area cannot be achieved without reform to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">further education funding system. We are therefore keen to discuss with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Education C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ommittee:</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the short </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">term, how councils can support employers to influence the commissioning of 16</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">19 provision across local economies to ensure young people benefit from local growth</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the longer term, the case for transferring the commissioning of 16</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-19</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> further education to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> local partnerships as part of a wider more coherent offer </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">supported</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by councils</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The principles of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a locally led</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> approach have been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">championed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a range of significant contributions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Heseltine Review, the Social Mobility Commission led by Alan Mi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lburn, and also the Work Foundation, London School of Economies, the Institute of Public Policy Research</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> among others.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Local authority tracking of young people</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local authorities have a responsibility to track young people as part of their statutory duties to encourage and support participation, and improve outcomes for young people.  </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ofsted’s Annual Report references the percentage of young people unknown to lo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cal authorities, which is on average 4 per cent of 16 and 17 year olds. It </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">states that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ‘in some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ocal authorities the percentage is as high as 23 per cent’. This is misleading. Only 7 councils have more than 10 per cent of young people unknown, only 2 coun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cils </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">above 15 per cent and only 1 council </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">above 20 per cent. Furthermore, in the last year, the percentage of young people unknown </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has fallen in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">each of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">these 7 councils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by as much as 13 per cent.  This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">improvement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not refe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">renced by the report. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Nevertheless</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> we are keen to support councils wanting to improve further, and the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> LGA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> recently launched a Tracking Guide and Planning Toolbox, which builds on the innovative practice in some ‘expert’ local authorities for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">those </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">want</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing to improve how they track young people</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. In undertaking this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">work,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">beca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">me clear that local authority success is dependent on the contribution </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> an increasingly fragmented market of providers in their area, accountable to national programmes. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">January 2014</span></p><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:left;"><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">1</span></p></div><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:18pt; widows:0"><span